05524nam a22008295i 9780812293012DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979834475  a97808122930127 a10.9783/97808122930122doi  a(DE-B1597)469690  a(OCoLC)951076329  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0380002bisacsh04a306.3/492231 aBurnard, Trevor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Plantation Machine :bAtlantic Capitalism in French Saint-Domingue and British Jamaica /cJohn Garrigus, Trevor Burnard. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b14 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMap -- t1. A Comparative History of Jamaica and Saint-Domingue -- t2. The Plantation World -- t3. Urban Life -- t4. The Seven Years’ War in the West Indies -- t5. Dangerous Internal Enemies -- t6. Racial Reconfigurations Before the American Revolution -- t7. The Golden Age of the Plantocracy -- t8. The American Revolution in the Greater Antilles -- t9. Recovery and Consolidation in the 1780s -- t10. The Ancien Régime in the Greater Antilles -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJamaica and Saint-Domingue were especially brutal but conspicuously successful eighteenth-century slave societies and imperial colonies. These plantation regimes were, to adopt a metaphor of the era, complex "machines," finely tuned over time by planters, merchants, and officials to become more efficient at exploiting their enslaved workers and serving their empires. Using a wide range of archival evidence, The Plantation Machine traces a critical half-century in the development of the social, economic, and political frameworks that made these societies possible. Trevor Burnard and John Garrigus find deep and unexpected similarities in these two prize colonies of empires that fought each other throughout the period. Jamaica and Saint-Domingue experienced, at nearly the same moment, a bitter feud between planters and governors, a violent conflict between masters and enslaved workers, a fateful tightening of racial laws, a steady expansion of the slave trade, and metropolitan criticism of planters' cruelty.The core of The Plantation Machine addresses the Seven Years' War and its aftermath. The events of that period, notably a slave poisoning scare in Saint-Domingue and a near-simultaneous slave revolt in Jamaica, cemented white dominance in both colonies. Burnard and Garrigus argue that local political concerns, not emerging racial ideologies, explain the rise of distinctive forms of racism in these two societies. The American Revolution provided another imperial crisis for the beneficiaries of the plantation machine, but by the 1780s whites in each place were prospering as never before—and blacks were suffering in new and disturbing ways. The result was that Jamaica and Saint-Domingue became vitally important parts of the late eighteenth-century American empires of Britain and France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPlantationsxHistoryxHaiti. 0aPlantationsxHistoryxJamaica. 0aPlantationszHaitixHistory. 0aPlantationszJamaicaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCaribbean Studies.  aEuropean History.  aLatin American Studies.  aWorld History.1 aGarrigus, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook pack